{"id":"2108.13404","submitter":"Urban Fasel","authors":"Urban Fasel, Eurika Kaiser, J. Nathan Kutz, Bingni W. Brunton, Steven\n  L. Brunton","title":"SINDy with Control: A Tutorial","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC math.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Many dynamical systems of interest are nonlinear, with examples in\nturbulence, epidemiology, neuroscience, and finance, making them difficult to\ncontrol using linear approaches. Model predictive control (MPC) is a powerful\nmodel-based optimization technique that enables the control of such nonlinear\nsystems with constraints. However, modern systems often lack computationally\ntractable models, motivating the use of system identification techniques to\nlearn accurate and efficient models for real-time control. In this tutorial\narticle, we review emerging data-driven methods for model discovery and how\nthey are used for nonlinear MPC. In particular, we focus on the sparse\nidentification of nonlinear dynamics (SINDy) algorithm and show how it may be\nused with MPC on an infectious disease control example. We compare the\nperformance against MPC based on a linear dynamic mode decomposition (DMD)\nmodel. Code is provided to run the tutorial examples and may be modified to\nextend this data-driven control framework to arbitrary nonlinear systems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 30 Aug 2021 17:48:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-31"}
