{"id":"2108.13634","submitter":"Mahmoud Abdelgalil","authors":"Mahmoud Abdelgalil, Yasser Aboelkassem and Haithem Taha","title":"Sea urchin sperm exploit extremum seeking control to find the egg","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.106.L062401","report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC physics.bio-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Sperm cells perform extremely demanding tasks with minimal capabilities. The\ncells must quickly navigate in a noisy environment to find an egg within a\nshort time window for successful fertilization without any global positioning\ninformation. Many research efforts have been dedicated to deriving mathematical\nprinciples that explain their superb navigation strategy. Here we show that the\nnavigation strategy of sea urchin sperm, also known as helical klinotaxis, is a\nnatural implementation of a well-established adaptive control paradigm known as\nextremum seeking. This bridge between control theory and the biology of taxis\nin microorganisms is expected to deepen our understanding of the process. For\nexample, the formulation leads to a coarse-grained model of the signaling\npathway that offers new insights on the peculiar switching-like behavior\nbetween high and low gain steering modes observed in sea urchin sperm.\nMoreover, it may guide engineers in developing bio-inspired miniaturized robots\nwith minimal sensors.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 31 Aug 2021 06:19:14 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 23 Nov 2021 22:31:10 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 12 Jan 2022 20:25:04 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 4 Oct 2022 22:56:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-21"}
