ithm. To match 2D ufSSFP MRI\ndata of pediatric patients, both CT data and segmentations were translated into\npseudo-MR images, masked to suppress anatomy outside the lung. Network-1 was\ntrained with pseudo-MR images and lobe segmentations, and applied to 1000\nmasked ufSSFP images to predict lobe segmentations. These outputs were directly\nused as targets to train Network-2 and Network-3 with non-masked ufSSFP data as\ninputs, and an additional whole-lung mask as input for Network-2. Network\npredictions were compared to reference manual lobe segmentations of ufSSFP data\nin twenty pediatric cystic fibrosis patients. Manual lobe segmentations were\nperformed by splitting available whole-lung segmentations into lobes.\n  Results: Network-1 was able to segment the lobes of ufSSFP images, and\nNetwork-2 and Network-3 further increased segmentation accuracy and robustness.\nThe average all-lobe Dice similarity coefficients were 95.0$\\pm$2.8\n(mean$\\pm$pooled SD [%]), 96.4$\\pm$2.0, 93.0$\\pm$2.0, and the average median\nHausdorff distances were 6.1$\\pm$0.9 (mean$\\pm$SD [mm]), 5.3$\\pm$1.1,\n7.1$\\pm$1.3, for Network-1, Network-2, and Network-3, respectively.\n  Conclusions: RNN lung lobe segmentation of 2D ufSSFP imaging is feasible, in\ngood agreement with manual segmentations. The proposed workflow might provide\naccess to automated lobe segmentations for various lung MRI examinations and\nquantitative analyses.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 31 Aug 2021 11:10:46 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 22 Dec 2021 20:39:22 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 14 Jan 2022 00:21:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-01-17"}
